[src:chemical-kinetics/rate-equation] Particular simple solutions exist in equilibrium, ${\frac {d[{\ce {X}}_{i}]}{dt}}=0$ , for systems composed of merely reversible reactions.
[src:chemical-kinetics/rate-equation] In this case, the rate of the forward and backward reactions are equal, a principle called detailed balance.
[src:chemical-kinetics/rate-equation] Detailed balance is a property of the stoichiometric matrix $N_{ij}$ alone and does not depend on the particular form of the rate functions $f_{j}$ .
[src:chemical-kinetics/rate-equation] All other cases where detailed balance is violated are commonly studied by flux balance analysis, which has been developed to understand metabolic pathways.
[src:chemical-kinetics/rate-equation] For a general unimolecular reaction involving interconversion of N different species, whose concentrations at time t are denoted by $X_{1}(t)$ through $X_{N}(t)$ , an analytic form for the time-evolution of the species can be found.
[src:chemical-kinetics/rate-equation] Let the rate constant of conversion from species $X_{i}$ to species $X_{j}$ be denoted as $k_{ij}$ , and construct a rate-constant matrix K whose entries are the $k_{ij}$ .
[src:chemical-kinetics/rate-equation] Let I be the $N\times N$ identity matrix.
[src:chemical-kinetics/rate-equation] Let $\operatorname {diag}$ be the function that takes a vector and constructs a diagonal matrix whose on-diagonal entries are those of the vector.
